Product description

0-100% Full Range Dimming

  • Set up wonderful Christmas lights according to your needs

Smart Dimming Function

  • Support to set different light brightness in different time periods.

Specifications for this item

  • It support most non-smart dimmable bulbs.
  • Working voltage: AC100V-240V 50/60Hz
  • Rated power(Resistive load): <200W
  • Protocol: WiFi
  • Wireless frequency: Only 2.4G, not 5G

  • Is the smart power Plug 1%~100% dimmable?

    Yes, it is 1%~100% brightness adjustable in APP for flexible lighting.

  • Does it support voice control on connected devices?

    Yes, you can give simple command to Alexa or Google home for controlling connected devices.

  • Does it support 5GHz？Does it need ahub？

    NO, it dont support 5GHz, only support 2.4GHz. And it does not need a hub.

      What’s to say? These are Tuya ecosphere devices. They work as advertised. I’ve read other reviews that complain they don’t work. That’s just not true. One particularly long review went into great detail about how they didn’t work. He was trying to get them to do something... See more
      What’s to say? These are Tuya ecosphere devices. They work as advertised. I’ve read other reviews that complain they don’t work. That’s just not true. One particularly long review went into great detail about how they didn’t work. He was trying to get them to do something they aren’t designed to do. Another person said they only worked as on-off. You MUST use a bulb that can be dimmed. Not all of them can. And, not all bulbs can be dimmed from 0% up to 100% in 1% increments. All the LED bulbs in my house stop producing light when they hit 25%. Does that mean the dimmer is busted? No. No it does not. The 25% bottom limit is a result of my lights - not the dimmer itself. These have worked for me controlling incandescent light bulbs, dimmable LED bulbs, and COB LED strips powered by transformers that are dimmable. They are easy to set up. And our Alexa network picks them up almost as soon as we plug them in. Don’t hesitate to buy these. But if you do, make sure you are using them as they are intended to be used. They aren’t magical. You can’t attach them to your coffee maker and expect them to dim the lights on the display. But if used as intended, they work without issue. I’ll be buying more as time goes on.

    • TimMan
      3.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Only works with Low Power Output
      Reviewed in the United States on September 16, 2023
      I bought this smart dimmer switch to control the lights that I had added to my porch. The lights that I added to my porch were low power, dimmable, LED string lights. I wanted to be able to use the smart switch to not only turn the power on and off, but also control the... See more
      I bought this smart dimmer switch to control the lights that I had added to my porch. The lights that I added to my porch were low power, dimmable, LED string lights. I wanted to be able to use the smart switch to not only turn the power on and off, but also control the intensity of the LED lights. The specs for the smart switch said that the switch would power lights up to 200 W.

      In my particular situation, each string of lights was listed at 15 W. I used three strings, for a total of 45 W of power. This smart switch would not dim the LED lights. When turned on, they stayed at full intensity, even though the software on the app was showing that the lights were being dimmed down to their minimum value.

      I submitted some questions regarding this issue on to the Amazon question site, but received no response from the manufacturer.

      So I did a few experiments on my own. I disconnected one of the strings so now I had only two of the strings for a total of 30 W connected to the switch. Still no dimming.

      When I took away the second string, so that there was only one string at 15 W on the smart switch, the smart switch finally was able to dim the LED lights.

      In order to make sure that I wasn’t overpowering switch, I used my current clamp meter and verified that the power on each string of lights was actually 15 W or less, which they were. So, I confirmed that the smart switch does not live up to it’s listed power capacity of 200 W.

      Another issue that I observed (which I also saw asked in the questions section) was whether the smart switch would stay in an “on” condition, if the power was turned off, for example at the wall switch.

      In my case, If the wall switch was on, and the smart switch was turned on with the app, the lights came on at full power. If the wall switch was then turned off and turned back on, the smart switch stayed off and had to again be turned back on using the app. The smart switch does not remember its last on condition. The smart switch defaults to an off condition when the source power is applied.

      A final note regarding the app for the smart switch. I found that it was a little difficult to get the smart switch connected to the app on my phone. I ultimately got the switch connected, but it took several tries to make it work. It seems like it should have been easier than it was.

      I would not recommend this smart switch and ended up returning my smart switch to Amazon as it didn’t work as specified.
